---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import TwoColumnLayout from "../layouts/TwoColumnLayout.astro";
import Ornament from "../components/Ornament.astro";
---

<BaseLayout title="Editorial Approach">
  <TwoColumnLayout>
    <article>
      <h1>Editorial Approach</h1>
      <p class="meta-text">How I think about problems</p>
      <p>
        The writing on this site is shaped by three intellectual traditions
        that I return to constantly in my work with leaders, organizations,
        and complex systems. They are not decorative references. They are
        the actual framework I use to decide what matters, what to let go of,
        and when something needs to be torn down so something better can
        be built.
      </p>

      <Ornament glyph="☙" />

      <h2>Stoicism</h2>
      <p>
        The Stoic tradition teaches the discipline of separating what is
        within your control from what is not&mdash;and investing your energy
        only in the former. Epictetus opens the <cite>Discourses</cite> with
        this distinction. Marcus Aurelius returns to it throughout the
        <cite>Meditations</cite>, writing to himself as a daily practice of
        recalibration. Seneca's <cite>Letters to Lucilius</cite> extend the
        idea into practical advice on managing time, setbacks, and the
        expectations of others.
      </p>
      <p>
        In enterprise work, this translates directly. Most of the anxiety
        in large-scale change comes from fixating on things outside your
        control&mdash;market timing, executive politics, inherited technical
        debt. Stoic practice redirects attention to the response: what can
        you actually do, right now, with what you have? <em>Premeditatio
        malorum</em>&mdash;the premeditation of adversity&mdash;is not
        pessimism. It is the disciplined habit of thinking through what
        could go wrong before it does, so that when it does, you act
        rather than react.
      </p>

      <Ornament glyph="☙" />

      <h2>Eastern Philosophy</h2>

      <h3>The Tao Te Ching</h3>
      <p>
        Lao Tzu's <cite>Tao Te Ching</cite> is the other lens I carry into
        every engagement. Where Stoicism provides discipline, the Tao
        provides disposition&mdash;a way of moving through situations that
        favors yielding over forcing, emptiness over accumulation, and
        patience over urgency.
      </p>
      <p>
        Chapter 76 teaches that the rigid and unyielding belong to death,
        while the soft and flexible belong to life. Chapter 11 observes that
        the usefulness of a vessel comes from its emptiness&mdash;a reminder
        that what is <em>not</em> there often matters more than what is.
        Chapter 22 counsels that by yielding, you overcome. These are not
        abstractions. They describe, with unsettling precision, how the best
        enterprise transformations actually work: not by imposing a vision
        from above, but by creating the conditions for the right thing to
        emerge.
      </p>
      <p>
        My primary translation is Brian Browne Walker's, though I continue
        to read across translations&mdash;each one surfaces something
        the others leave in shadow.
      </p>

      <h3>Shiva: Destruction as Creation</h3>
      <p>
        The Hindu tradition of Shiva as destroyer and creator provides
        something that Stoicism and Taoism, on their own, do not: explicit
        permission to tear things down. Shiva's <em>tandava</em>&mdash;the
        cosmic dance of destruction and renewal&mdash;holds that creation
        is not possible without the dissolution of what came before. The old
        must be consumed so the new can emerge from its ashes.
      </p>
      <p>
        In the Western tradition, Joseph Schumpeter arrived at a parallel
        insight with his concept of "creative destruction"&mdash;the
        recognition that economic progress requires the continuous
        dismantling of existing structures. But where Schumpeter described
        a mechanism, the Shaiva tradition describes a <em>disposition</em>:
        not just that destruction happens, but that it is sacred, necessary,
        and should be approached with intention rather than regret.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is the hardest part of enterprise work. Knowing that a legacy
        system, a team structure, or a business model must be dismantled
        is one thing. Having the conviction to do it&mdash;and the
        framework to know <em>when</em>&mdash;is another.
      </p>

      <Ornament glyph="☙" />

      <h2>Pace Layers</h2>
      <p>
        Stewart Brand introduced the pace layers framework in
        <cite>The Clock of the Long Now</cite> (1999) and later refined it
        in "Pace Layering: How Complex Systems Learn," published in the
        <cite>Journal of Design and Science</cite> (MIT Media Lab, 2018).
        The model describes civilization&mdash;and, by extension, any
        complex system&mdash;as a stack of layers, each moving at a
        different speed:
      </p>
      <dl class="pace-layers-diagram">
        <div class="pace-layer-row">
          <dt>Fashion / Art</dt>
          <dd>The fastest layer. Trends, experimentation, novelty. It moves quickly, fails cheaply, and generates the variation from which slower layers eventually select.</dd>
        </div>
        <div class="pace-layer-row">
          <dt>Commerce</dt>
          <dd>Markets, business models, economic incentives. Faster than governance but constrained by it. Commerce amplifies what fashion invents and discards what cannot sustain itself.</dd>
        </div>
        <div class="pace-layer-row">
          <dt>Infrastructure</dt>
          <dd>Roads, networks, platforms, protocols. Slow to build, expensive to change, and foundational to everything above it. In technology: APIs, data models, deployment pipelines.</dd>
        </div>
        <div class="pace-layer-row">
          <dt>Governance</dt>
          <dd>Laws, regulations, institutional structures. Governance absorbs the lessons of faster layers and codifies them. It is deliberately slow so that it can be deliberately stable.</dd>
        </div>
        <div class="pace-layer-row">
          <dt>Culture</dt>
          <dd>Deep values, identity, shared assumptions. Culture changes across generations, not quarters. It is the layer that determines what a society&mdash;or an organization&mdash;is willing to tolerate.</dd>
        </div>
        <div class="pace-layer-row">
          <dt>Nature</dt>
          <dd>The slowest layer. Geology, climate, biology. Nature operates on timescales that make human planning look like a rounding error. It is the foundation everything else rests on.</dd>
        </div>
      </dl>
      <p>
        Brand's core insight is that the health of the system depends on
        each layer respecting its pace. Fast layers innovate; slow layers
        stabilize. Fast layers propose; slow layers dispose. When a fast
        layer tries to force change on a slow layer&mdash;or when a slow
        layer suppresses the speed of a fast one&mdash;the system breaks.
      </p>

      <Ornament glyph="☙" />

      <h2>The Synthesis</h2>
      <p>
        These three traditions converge in my work:
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Pace Layers</strong> provides the structural map. What layer
        are you operating in? What is its natural speed? What layers sit
        above and below you, and how are they exerting pressure?
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Stoicism</strong> provides the discipline. Within the layer
        you occupy, what is actually within your control? What must you
        accept? Where should you invest your energy, and where should you
        let go?
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>The Tao Te Ching</strong> provides the disposition. When the
        layer demands patience, yield. When rigidity would break what
        flexibility would preserve, be water. When the right action is
        no action, have the composure to wait.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Shiva</strong> provides the permission. When a layer is ripe
        for destruction&mdash;when the legacy system cannot be reformed,
        when the organizational structure is actively preventing the work
        it was designed to support&mdash;have the conviction to tear it
        down. Some layers must be destroyed before they can be renewed.
        Knowing when that moment has arrived is the hardest judgment call
        in enterprise work.
      </p>
      <p>
        Articles on this site are annotated with the pace layers they
        touch. You will find these annotations at the end of each piece,
        noting which layers the argument engages and why. The annotations
        are my way of making the framework visible rather than leaving
        it implicit.
      </p>

      <Ornament glyph="☙" />

      <p>
        For professional biography, see <a href="/about">About</a>.
      </p>
    </article>
  </TwoColumnLayout>
</BaseLayout>
